{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C9Z6BYoFvHDNeoU5HiG9iF","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n    Date: 2026-06-23\n    Auditor: Automated Compliance Scan (read-only)\n    ============================================================\n\n    == COMPLIANT ITEMS ==\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-1: Dedicated service account\n      A dedicated 'spark-pi' service account is used by all workloads\n      (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job). The 'default' service\n      account is not used for any workload.\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-2: Namespace-scoped role (not ClusterRole)\n      'spark-pi-role' is a Role (not ClusterRole), limiting RBAC permissions\n      to the spark-pi namespace only. Blast radius is namespace-contained.\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-3: RoleBinding correctly targets dedicated SA\n      'spark-pi-role-binding' binds 'spark-pi-role' to the 'spark-pi'\n      service account in the correct namespace.\n\n    [PASS] RESOURCES-1: CPU/memory requests and limits set on all containers\n      All three workloads (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) have:\n        requests: cpu=200m, memory=512Mi\n        limits:   cpu=500m, memory=1Gi\n      Prevents unbounded resource consumption.\n\n    [PASS] IMAGE-1: Versioned image tag (not 'latest')\n      All containers use 'apache/spark:3.5.3'. The ':latest' anti-pattern\n      is avoided, ensuring reproducible deployments.\n\n    [PASS] IMAGE-2: imagePullPolicy set to IfNotPresent\n      All containers use imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent, preventing\n      unnecessary re-pulls and enforcing image stability at runtime.\n\n    [PASS] JOB-1: backoffLimit=0 on spark-pi job\n      The spark-pi batch job has backoffLimit=0, preventing automatic\n      retries on failure and avoiding runaway job costs.\n\n    [PASS] JOB-2: Job completed successfully\n      The spark-pi job completed (status: Complete, succeeded=1,\n      completionTime: 2026-06-23T21:33:57Z).\n\n    ============================================================\n\n    == NON-COMPLIANT ITEMS / GAPS ==\n\n    [FAIL] SEC-1 [CRITICAL]: No pod or container security context on any workload\n      All three workloads (spark-master Deployment, spark-worker Deployment,\n      spark-pi Job) have securityContext: {} at both pod and container level.\n      Missing controls:\n        - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers likely run as root)\n        - runAsUser / runAsGroup  (no UID/GID pinning)\n        - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n        - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true\n        - capabilities.drop: [ALL]\n      Risk: containers with root access can escalate privileges and access\n      sensitive host resources if container isolation is breached.\n      Remediation: add a securityContext block to each pod and container spec.\n\n    [FAIL] RBAC-4 [HIGH]: 'pods' resource added to role beyond original declaration\n      The live 'spark-pi-role' grants create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch\n      on 'pods' in addition to services, configmaps, and persistentvolumeclaims.\n      The kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration annotation shows the\n      role was originally created WITHOUT the 'pods' resource. The 'pods' entry\n      was added post-creation, representing an undeclared permission expansion.\n      For a SparkPi job running in local[2] mode (no dynamic executor pod\n      allocation), pod CRUD permissions are unnecessary.\n      Risk: the spark-pi SA can create, delete, or modify pods in this namespace,\n      enabling potential lateral movement or workload manipulation.\n      Remediation: remove 'pods' from the role's resource list.\n\n    [FAIL] NET-1 [HIGH]: No NetworkPolicy defined\n      The spark-pi namespace has zero NetworkPolicy objects. All pod-to-pod\n      traffic within the namespace and from other namespaces is unrestricted.\n      The Spark master WebUI (port 8080) and Spark protocol port (7077) are\n      reachable by any pod in the cluster.\n      Risk: unrestricted lateral movement; any compromised pod in the cluster\n      can connect to Spark master/worker endpoints.\n      Remediation: create NetworkPolicy resources to restrict ingress/egress\n      to only required ports and sources.\n\n    [FAIL] QUOTA-1 [MEDIUM]: No LimitRange or ResourceQuota in namespace\n      No LimitRange or ResourceQuota objects exist in spark-pi. Resource\n      limits on current workloads are set voluntarily; future workloads\n      (or a modified manifest) could omit limits and run unconstrained.\n      Risk: noisy-neighbor resource exhaustion affecting the cluster.\n      Remediation: add a LimitRange with default limits and a ResourceQuota\n      to cap total namespace consumption.\n\n    [FAIL] IMAGE-3 [MEDIUM]: Image not pinned to immutable digest\n      'apache/spark:3.5.3' is a mutable tag. A registry push could change\n      what this tag resolves to without changing the manifest.\n      Risk: supply-chain substitution; undetected image replacement.\n      Remediation: pin images to 'apache/spark@sha256:<digest>' for\n      immutable, verifiable provenance.\n\n    [FAIL] RBAC-5 [LOW]: 'default' service account lacks automountServiceAccountToken=false\n      The 'default' service account in spark-pi does not set\n      automountServiceAccountToken: false. Any pod that omits a\n      serviceAccountName (e.g. a misconfigured or injected workload) will\n      automatically mount a 'default' SA token.\n      Risk: unintended API access from pods that should have no cluster access.\n      Remediation: patch the 'default' SA with automountServiceAccountToken: false.\n\n    ============================================================\n\n    == SUMMARY ==\n\n    Total checks: 14\n      Passed (compliant):    8\n      Failed (gaps/issues):  6\n        Critical: 1 (SEC-1 — no security context)\n        High:     2 (RBAC-4 pod permissions drift, NET-1 no NetworkPolicy)\n        Medium:   2 (QUOTA-1 no LimitRange/Quota, IMAGE-3 mutable tag)\n        Low:      1 (RBAC-5 default SA token automount)\n\n    NOTE: This is a read-only audit. No changes were made to the cluster.\n    Remediation should be planned and applied separately after review.\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-23T21:35:28Z\"\n  name: config-audit\n  namespace: spark-pi\n  resourceVersion: \"909053\"\n  uid: 02f854c2-c711-4c4e-b780-2d99b442c6f7","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b256bcd2-55cd-49cd-8262-d0cab05d5831","uuid":"8dfb0893-746f-4ae8-a071-f201ebf755eb","timestamp":"2026-06-23T21:35:58.480Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n    Date: 2026-06-23\n    Auditor: Automated Compliance Scan (read-only)\n    ============================================================\n\n    == COMPLIANT ITEMS ==\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-1: Dedicated service account\n      A dedicated 'spark-pi' service account is used by all workloads\n      (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job). The 'default' service\n      account is not used for any workload.\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-2: Namespace-scoped role (not ClusterRole)\n      'spark-pi-role' is a Role (not ClusterRole), limiting RBAC permissions\n      to the spark-pi namespace only. Blast radius is namespace-contained.\n\n    [PASS] RBAC-3: RoleBinding correctly targets dedicated SA\n      'spark-pi-role-binding' binds 'spark-pi-role' to the 'spark-pi'\n      service account in the correct namespace.\n\n    [PASS] RESOURCES-1: CPU/memory requests and limits set on all containers\n      All three workloads (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) have:\n        requests: cpu=200m, memory=512Mi\n        limits:   cpu=500m, memory=1Gi\n      Prevents unbounded resource consumption.\n\n    [PASS] IMAGE-1: Versioned image tag (not 'latest')\n      All containers use 'apache/spark:3.5.3'. The ':latest' anti-pattern\n      is avoided,